The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	Calcutta: Inderjit Singh Bindra, the Punjab Cricket Association chief, Thursday threw his weight behind Lalit Modi, saying that the suspended IPL chairman and commissioner should be given a fair trial. Bindra said the IPL owed its success to the marketing skills of Modi and appealed for the embattled administrator to be given a fair hearing while at the same time taking a dim view of the controversy. Let us not forget that everyone is entitled to a fair trial part of the blame lies with our own cricketing fraternity for being an instrumental in leaking all kinds of unconfirmed reports without veracity or merit, Bindra said in a statement.        
	Calcutta: The Sir Vivian Richards Stadium in Antigua has been passed fit to host international cricket again after being suspended for 12 months due to a pitch fiasco, the ICC said.        
	Melbourne: Australia fast bowler Brett Lee is gutted by his latest injury which ruled him out of the World T20 but it is unlikely to end his international career, Cricket Australia physio Alex Kountouris has said.         
	Mumbai: The Mumbai Cricket Association will raise the issue of the humiliation inflicted on former India captain Nari Contractor at this seasons IPL finale at the upcoming BCCI working committee meeting. Contractor had to return without witnessing the April 25 final as his ticket was declared invalid.        
	New Delhi: Top seeds Rohan Bopanna and Aisam-ul Haq Qureshi lost 5-7, 6-3, 9-11 against Frederico Gel and Marcelo Melo to bow out in the quarters of the ATP Tunis Open .        
	Calcutta: Shivika Burman lost 3-6, 1-6 against Zlochova Zuzana of Slovakia in the $10,000 ITF Womens Circuit being played at Antalya, Turkey.        
	 London: F1s KERS systems, scrapped by teams last year as too costly, could make a comeback next season in a cheaper and more powerful guise. Williams technical director Sam Michael has said.       
	New Delhi:The trio of Vikas Krishan, J. Bhaskar and Shiva Thapa advanced to the quarter finals of the World Youth boxing Championships in Azerbaijan on Thursday.
        
	New Delhi: Sunil Chetri scored in the Kansas City Wizards 7-1 thrashing of Baker University in a friendly match in Kansas City.                                                                                                                                                      
